<p><big><b><font color="#800000"><big>Rayleigh Resolution Criterion</big><br>
</font><font color="#008040">Image of Two Off-Axis Point Sources</b> </font></big></p>

<p>Now let us consider the case in which there are two identical monochromatic incoherent
point sources, <em>S</em><sub><small>1</small></sub>and <em>S</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>,
lying in the same plane, a plane which is parallel to the lens, and which is very far from
it. Furthermore, let these two sources be symmetrically positioned about the axis of the
lens, each making a small angle <em><font FACE="Symbol">q</font></em>/2 with the axis, as
is shown in Figure 4. In Figure 4, <em>P</em><sub><small>1</small></sub> is the
geometrical optics image of <em>S</em><sub><small>1</small></sub> and <em>P</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>
is the geometrical optics image of <em>S</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>.</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><p align="center"><img align="absmiddle" src="../images/two-source-diagram.gif" alt="two-source-diagram.gif (2020 bytes)" WIDTH="593" HEIGHT="215"></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><small>Figure 4:&nbsp; Geometrical optics imaging of two distant off-axis
    point sources.</small></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>Let <em>P</em>=(<em>x</em>,<em>y</em>) be a point in the focal plane. Let <em>I</em><small><sub>1</sub></small>(<em>x</em>,0)
be the intensity at <i>P </i>due to <em>S</em><small><sub>1</sub></small> and let <em>I</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>(<em>x</em>,<em>y</em>)
be the intensity at <i>P </i>due to <em>S</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>. It follows from
Figure 4 that <em>I</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>(<em>x</em>,0) is centered about the
point <em>P</em><small><sub>1</sub></small>=(<em>f</em><font FACE="Symbol">×</font>tan(<em><font FACE="Symbol">q</font></em>/2),0)<font FACE="Symbol">»</font>(<em>f<font FACE="Symbol">q</font></em>/2,0)
in the focal plane and that <em>I</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>(<em>x</em>,<em>y</em>)
is centered about the point <em>P</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>=(-<em>f</em><font FACE="Symbol">×</font>tan(<em><font FACE="Symbol">q</font></em>/2),0)<font FACE="Symbol">»</font>(-<em>f<font FACE="Symbol">q</font></em>/2,0). Since the two sources are incoherent with respect to
each other, the total intensity at any point in the focal plane is sum of their individual
intensities, i.e.,</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"><p align="center"><em>I</em>(<em>x</em>, <em>y</em>) =<em> I</em><small><sub>1</sub></small>(<em>x</em>,
    <em>y</em>) +<em> I</em><small><sub>2</sub></small>(<em>x</em>, <em>y</em>) </td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right">(2.1)</td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

